{"query": "In degraded forest areas, what interventions are available to improve soil conditions and enhance tree growth?", "summary": "Multiple interventions are available to improve soil conditions and enhance tree growth in degraded forest areas. Ground preparation before tree planting has shown positive effects, with six of seven studies finding that ground preparation treatments increased the survival and growth rate of planted trees (action 1263). Soil disturbance techniques include scarification or ploughing, where two of three studies found that ploughing increased the density of young trees, and two replicated controlled studies found mixed effects of tilling on different tree species (action 1251). Vegetation removal combined with mechanical soil disturbance increased the cover and diversity of understory plants and increased the density of young trees (action 1274).

Fertilizer application has demonstrated benefits, with six of eight studies finding that applying fertilizer increased total plant cover, understory plant biomass, size of young trees, and cover of seeded plant species (action 1248). Organic fertilizer shows specific advantages over inorganic fertilizer, with eight replicated studies finding more organic matter in soils with organic fertilizer compared to inorganic fertilizer, and four studies finding more microbial biomass in soils with organic fertilizer (action 1366). Adding organic matter to soil shows mixed results, with one study finding that leaf litter addition increased species richness of young trees, and another study finding that adding plant material to the soil surface increased total plant cover (action 1250).

Soil amendments using a mix of organic and inorganic materials have proven effective, with five controlled trials finding higher microbial biomass and activity in soils with mixed manure and inorganic fertilizers, and four trials finding more organic carbon in soils with mixed fertilizers (action 902). Formulated chemical compounds can also improve soil conditions, with five of six studies showing increased soil organic matter or carbon when nitrogen or phosphorus fertilizer was applied (action 909). However, specific soil enhancers after tree planting showed mixed results, with different soil enhancers having mixed effects on tree seedling survival and height (action 1153). Mycorrhizal inoculation shows some promise, with studies finding that inoculating soil with mycorrhizal fungi before planting increased vegetation cover and height of certain plant species (action 3429).", "action_ids": ["1263","1251","1274","1248","1366","1250","902","909","1153","3429"]}

